00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:48.790
Lessons from her course are applied in companies
throughout the world, including here at Google

00:00:48.790 --> 00:00:52.430
where we have a program called CSI that teaches
many of the same things

00:00:52.430 --> 00:00:53.850
that were taught in her class.

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:56.840
Um,Together, with other proud alumni
in her class here at Google

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:59.422
in the audience,
please join me in welcoming Tina back to Google.

00:00:59.422 --> 00:01:00.422
Thank you.

00:01:00.422 --> 00:01:01.422
[applause]
&gt;&gt;Tina Seelig: Thanks so much.

00:01:01.422 --> 00:01:02.422
Thank you

00:01:02.422 --> 00:01:08.850
&gt;&gt;Tina Seelig: It is my total pleasure to
be back here again.

00:01:08.850 --> 00:01:11.920
It was exactly three years ago that I was
here giving you

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:15.700
a talk about my last book "What I Wish I Knew
When I Was Twenty."

00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:19.210
Who would have known that three years later
I would have a new book out and would get

00:01:19.210 --> 00:01:20.660
to share with you.

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:26.460
This book is based on my dozen years teaching
classes on creativity and innovation

00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:28.290
and entrepreneurship at Stanford.

00:01:28.290 --> 00:01:33.470
And I decided I wanted to capture
what I've learned through these experiences.

00:01:33.470 --> 00:01:36.409
And uh it's interesting, I had lunch
with some of the Googlers today,

00:01:36.409 --> 00:01:40.970
and they asked how I got
from being neurophysiologist to being a,

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:44.210
you know, teaching classes on
creativity and innovation.

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:48.010
And it turns out, I really went into
neuroscience initially because

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:49.869
of my interest in creativity.

00:01:49.869 --> 00:01:52.460
I wanted to know how the brain generated ideas.

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:54.790
And I have to say that, after finishing four
years

00:01:54.790 --> 00:01:58.610
of my PH.D at Stanford,
um, I realized we were still pretty far

00:01:58.610 --> 00:02:02.540
from understanding how the brain works
and how creativity is generated.

00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:06.020
So I went out into the real world
to look at creativity in action.

00:02:06.020 --> 00:02:10.529
I've worked in startup companies,
and I'm just delighted to be at Stanford now

00:02:10.529 --> 00:02:11.799
for just over a dozen years.

00:02:11.799 --> 00:02:16.859
Uh, really focusing on this, on creativity
in individuals, in teams and organizations.

00:02:16.859 --> 00:02:21.109
The First question I want to ask is:
Where do ideas come from?

00:02:21.109 --> 00:02:22.410
Where do ideas come from?

00:02:22.410 --> 00:02:23.410
Anyone?

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:24.410
&gt;&gt;audience member: Inspiration
&gt;&gt;Tina:

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:25.689
From Inspiration.

00:02:25.689 --> 00:02:26.689
And where do you get inspiration?

00:02:26.689 --> 00:02:31.900
&gt;&gt;audience member: From putting two unconnected
things together as an example

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:33.329
&gt;&gt;Tina: Great!

00:02:33.329 --> 00:02:34.330
Connecting things that are unconnected.

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:35.330
What else?

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:36.780
&gt;&gt;audience member: [inaudible]

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:37.879
&gt;&gt;Tina: From your environment.

00:02:37.879 --> 00:02:41.109
You know, the interesting thing here is if
I had asked you

00:02:41.109 --> 00:02:45.019
How do you do experiments to figure out how
the world works?

00:02:45.019 --> 00:02:48.110
you would end up coming up with some very
very clear ideas

00:02:48.110 --> 00:02:50.379
about how to do a science experiment.

00:02:50.379 --> 00:02:53.949
From the time
we are little, we are given classes and taught

00:02:53.949 --> 00:02:56.129
how to come up with hypotheses and how to
test them,

00:02:56.129 --> 00:02:58.739
how to analyze the data, and basically how
to discover

00:02:58.739 --> 00:02:59.959
how the world works.

00:02:59.959 --> 00:03:04.609
But we aren't given
a parallel set of processes to think about

00:03:04.609 --> 00:03:06.529
how to invent
new things.

00:03:06.529 --> 00:03:11.059
Now here you are in Google where there is
invention, invention going on all the time,

00:03:11.059 --> 00:03:13.769
but one of the things
that happens is, we aren't actually really

00:03:13.769 --> 00:03:17.879
clear about all
the variables that are coming into play.

00:03:17.879 --> 00:03:21.829
So what I've been trying to do is figure out
a way, a model,

00:03:21.829 --> 00:03:24.919
that shapes how we think about creativity
and innovation

00:03:24.919 --> 00:03:26.590
in individuals, in teams and organizations.

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:31.889
So...I am going to start out
by showing you a picture of this model,

00:03:31.889 --> 00:03:34.939
and I'm going to take it apart and put it
back together.

00:03:34.939 --> 00:03:40.650
The model I call "The Innovation Engine",
and it looks at the things that happen inside

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:42.939
you,
the inside of this Mobius strip:

00:03:42.939 --> 00:03:46.799
your knowledge, information, attitude
and the outside, the things that have to come

00:03:46.799 --> 00:03:48.829
into play
in the outside world:

00:03:48.829 --> 00:03:51.709
the resources, habitat and the culture.

00:03:51.709 --> 00:03:54.749
Now the interesting thing is if you ask most
people

00:03:54.749 --> 00:03:57.389
to make a list of the things
that are important for creativity,

00:03:57.389 --> 00:04:00.819
they usually start with imagination.

00:04:00.819 --> 00:04:02.870
Because that's the obvious place to start.

00:04:02.870 --> 00:04:04.159
So we're going to start there too....

00:04:04.159 --> 00:04:08.339
....With your imagination.

00:04:08.339 --> 00:04:11.699
Now, we're actually all imaginative.

00:04:11.699 --> 00:04:16.859
We wouldn't be sitting here, or standing here,
uh, where we are if we hadn't been.

00:04:16.859 --> 00:04:21.940
We had to learn through creative problem solving
in every single aspect of our lives, right?

00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:24.840
Walking, talking, riding a bicycle,
and certainly all of the products you are

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:25.840
developing here today.

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:30.039
But why is it that many people don't
think of themselves as creative?

00:04:30.039 --> 00:04:34.520
And a lot of it comes from the type of training
and environments that we've been in.

00:04:34.520 --> 00:04:35.740
Think about it...

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:38.340
When we're in Kindergarten, we're given problems
like this....

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:43.831
..What two numbers add up to ten? or, if
we are given five and five, what's the answer?

00:04:43.831 --> 00:04:44.919
what's the answer to this?

00:04:44.919 --> 00:04:46.129
&gt;&gt;audience member: [inaudible]

00:04:46.129 --> 00:04:47.340
&gt;&gt;Tina:
Ten, okay.

00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:48.889
I got a little ahead of myself there.

00:04:48.889 --> 00:04:51.270
Okay, if we're given this, there's one right
answer

00:04:51.270 --> 00:04:53.810
because we're taught that one right answer.

00:04:53.810 --> 00:04:56.759
But what if we ask the question in a different
way?

00:04:56.759 --> 00:05:00.560
What if we ask what two numbers add up to
ten?

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:02.560
How many answers are there to this?

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:05.630
&gt;&gt;audience member: infinite answers

00:05:05.630 --> 00:05:07.939
&gt;&gt;Tina: Infinite answers.

00:05:07.939 --> 00:05:10.639
You can of course
take the obvious answers like eight plus two,

00:05:10.639 --> 00:05:14.300
and three plus seven, but negative numbers,
fractions,

00:05:14.300 --> 00:05:17.340
decimals, and if we don't ask questions in
the right way,

00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:19.659
we don't come up with the right answers.

00:05:19.659 --> 00:05:22.830
And this is very very important,
because one of the first steps in increasing

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:27.050
your imagination
is asking the right question.

00:05:27.050 --> 00:05:28.050
Think about it.

00:05:28.050 --> 00:05:31.120
If I ask you, um, if you'll build a bridge
for me,

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:34.560
you could go off and build a bridge,
or you could come back to me and say,

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:36.879
"Why do we need a bridge in the first place?"

00:05:36.879 --> 00:05:42.750
And if I said "I need to get across the Bay",
wow, there are so many ways to do that, right?

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:46.830
You could walk around, you could swim,
you could take a boat, you could have a helicopter,

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:49.240
you could have a tunnel, you could have a
hot air balloon.

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:52.960
The fact is if we don't ask
the question properly in the beginning,

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:55.220
we don't end up coming with the right answers.

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:57.530
Or the whole field of possible answers.

00:05:57.530 --> 00:06:02.030
Albert Einstein is quoted as saying
if he had a problem to solve,

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:05.970
and it was terribly difficult,
and his life depended upon it,

00:06:05.970 --> 00:06:11.629
and he only had an hour to solve the problem...
he'd spend the first fifty-five minutes

00:06:11.629 --> 00:06:14.939
framing the problem,
because the frame of the problem

00:06:14.939 --> 00:06:17.729
is essentially the frame
in which the answers will fall.

00:06:17.729 --> 00:06:20.220
And so we have to think about practicing this.

00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:21.870
This is NOT trivial.

00:06:21.870 --> 00:06:25.520
If you think about it,
the entire Copernican revolution came about

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:28.460
by reframing what we think of the solar system.

00:06:28.460 --> 00:06:30.990
Instead of saying the Earth is the center
of the solar system,

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:34.419
by reframing it and saying
"Wow what would happen if the sun was the

00:06:34.419 --> 00:06:35.960
center of the solar system?"

00:06:35.960 --> 00:06:39.470
All of a sudden it opened up the entire field
of astronomy.

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:42.960
This is not just true in science,
this is true in art as well.

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:45.940
Think of artists like Escher
who challenge us to look,

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:48.030
question the foreground, and the background.

00:06:48.030 --> 00:06:52.909
And most of his artwork really looks at changing
the way we frame the picture.

00:06:52.909 --> 00:06:56.509
There's some really fun ways to practice
doing this every day.

00:06:56.509 --> 00:06:57.529
Really fun ways.

00:06:57.529 --> 00:07:00.319
My favorite way to do it using jokes.

00:07:00.319 --> 00:07:06.039
So, um, you guys are probably familiar
with the Pink Panther, the Pink Panther

00:07:06.039 --> 00:07:13.550
and Inspector Clouseau, uh looks at a dog
on the street and he's about to go and pet

00:07:13.550 --> 00:07:14.999
him
and he says "Does your dog bite?"

00:07:14.999 --> 00:07:19.050
and, uh, the, uh, person who's carrying the
dog says,

00:07:19.050 --> 00:07:20.150
"No, my dog doesn't bite."

00:07:20.150 --> 00:07:23.080
He reaches down, dog bites him and he says,
"What happened?"

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:25.520
and he says "Well, that's not my dog."

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:26.660
[crowd laughs]

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:30.460
The fact is the frame changes in the middle,
and this happens all the time.

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:34.340
If you look at jokes, you will find that jokes
are funny because the frame switches.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:37.479
Here's an example:
Two women are walking, uh, playing golf one

00:07:37.479 --> 00:07:41.379
day,
and, uh a funeral goes by, in the cemetery

00:07:41.379 --> 00:07:45.039
next door,
and one of them stops, quietly bows her head

00:07:45.039 --> 00:07:48.659
and says a prayer,
and her friend says "You are the most thoughtful

00:07:48.659 --> 00:07:50.159
person
I could ever imagine!"

00:07:50.159 --> 00:07:52.129
She says, "Well, it's the least I could do.

00:07:52.129 --> 00:07:53.490
We were married for
twenty-five years."

00:07:53.490 --> 00:07:54.669
[crowd laughs]

00:07:54.669 --> 00:07:57.599
Again, the frame switched in the middle of
the joke.

00:07:57.599 --> 00:07:58.750
THAT's what makes it funny.

00:07:58.750 --> 00:08:06.129
So look at jokes as way for you to practice,
even on a day to day level, how to frame problems.

00:08:06.129 --> 00:08:09.789
Now, another way to increase your imagination,
and you brought this up earlier,

00:08:09.789 --> 00:08:13.190
is to connect and combine things that are
not obvious.

00:08:13.190 --> 00:08:18.219
And this is an incredibly powerful tool,
because most new inventions actually come

00:08:18.219 --> 00:08:21.689
about
by putting things together that already exist

00:08:21.689 --> 00:08:23.669
but in non-obvious ways.

00:08:23.669 --> 00:08:29.879
One of my favorite ways to explore this is
looking at the Japanese art of Chindogu.

00:08:29.879 --> 00:08:32.820
And the art of Chindogu is creating unuseless
inventions.

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:39.740
Now these are things that aren't really useful,
and they're not really useless, but they are

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:40.789
kind of unuseful.

00:08:40.789 --> 00:08:44.120
So here's an example, you know, the shoes
with the, uh, uh,

00:08:44.120 --> 00:08:45.120
umbrellas on them.

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:49.339
Well, it might not be completely practical,
but opens up a really interesting set of ideas,

00:08:49.339 --> 00:08:53.660
and you'd say "Whoa, what might that be if
we had an equivalent

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:55.860
to umbrellas on our shoes?"

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:59.840
Or speaking of shoes, what if we had little
[laughter] dustpans on our shoes?

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:02.649
Now I would say, this is actually really interesting.

00:09:02.649 --> 00:09:06.350
We normally have to get down on the floor
to sweep things up,

00:09:06.350 --> 00:09:10.880
what kind of ideas does this unlock by thinking
about what happens if you put a dustpan your

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:12.000
shoes?

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.130
Or what if you put a mop on a baby's tummy,
right?

00:09:16.130 --> 00:09:19.130
Why not, if instead of the baby making a mess,
the baby's job

00:09:19.130 --> 00:09:20.870
is to clean up [crowd laughs] after itself
okay?

00:09:20.870 --> 00:09:23.680
[crowd laughs]
So as it's , you put it on the floor, you

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:26.160
know, sort of like
better than a little robot, you know, the

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:28.019
baby crawls around,
cleans up the floor.

00:09:28.019 --> 00:09:29.019
Okay.

00:09:29.019 --> 00:09:33.550
So you have framing problems, you have
connecting and combining ideas, it's also

00:09:33.550 --> 00:09:36.399
important,
no, uh, this is an example of an uh, every

00:09:36.399 --> 00:09:38.190
day way to combine and connect ideas.

00:09:38.190 --> 00:09:41.970
One of my favorite approaches is uh using
the New Yorker Cartoon contest.

00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:43.770
How many of you read the New Yorker?

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:44.770
Lots of you?

00:09:44.770 --> 00:09:45.770
okay.

00:09:45.770 --> 00:09:46.770
It's one of my favorite things, um, and in
the back,

00:09:46.770 --> 00:09:50.630
there is the contest where there's cartoon
that has not captions,

00:09:50.630 --> 00:09:54.720
and there's almost always things that are
incongruent that are in the picture.

00:09:54.720 --> 00:09:57.520
Things that shouldn't be together, things
that are out of scale,

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:00.520
things that seem ridiculous when you put them
in the same frame.

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:04.019
And it's your job to connect them, to create
some storyline that in a really

00:10:04.019 --> 00:10:05.760
fun and interesting way connects them.

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:10.040
So here's a picture of two businessmen and
a hobby horse,

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:13.810
and here is the caption that they had,
"We'll start you out here, then give you more

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:15.380
responsibilities
as you gain experience."

00:10:15.380 --> 00:10:16.380
[crowd laughs]

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:17.790
Maybe that could happen here at Google.

00:10:17.790 --> 00:10:18.790
I don't know.

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:19.790
[crowd laughs]

00:10:19.790 --> 00:10:21.120
So, I said you've got to connect and combine
ideas,

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:25.800
you've to reframe problems, you also need
to challenge assumptions.

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:27.250
Now what does this mean?

00:10:27.250 --> 00:10:30.410
This is actually critically important
for your imagination.

00:10:30.410 --> 00:10:36.070
It means going beyond the first right answer.

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:39.690
Most of us, when we try to solve a problem,
come up with the first answer

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:41.170
and think we're done.

00:10:41.170 --> 00:10:45.730
And this is terribly problematic if you
want to come up with a really creative solution.

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:48.829
And it's one of the reasons that we do brainstorming,
because brainstorming is a great way, if used

00:10:48.829 --> 00:10:52.850
properly,
to really generate a LOT of ideas, often ideas

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:53.880
that are unexpected.

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:56.699
The way I like to teach my students to challenge
assumptions

00:10:56.699 --> 00:11:00.220
is that I give them problems that don't have
a right answer.

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:03.320
In fact, they are problems I have no idea
how I would tackle

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:05.649
and so I want to be as surprised by the types
of results

00:11:05.649 --> 00:11:06.940
they come up with as they are.

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:11.860
Uh, let me tell you a story
about a recent project I gave:

00:11:11.860 --> 00:11:13.170
This was in Japan.

00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:18.449
I was asked to run, um, a couple of workshops
with students at Osaka University.

00:11:18.449 --> 00:11:22.269
I want to frame this by saying
I was told I'm going there because these students

00:11:22.269 --> 00:11:25.449
are NOT creative,
and they kind of wanted to prove it to me.

00:11:25.449 --> 00:11:28.579
And I said "No no no no
your students are amazingly creative, and

00:11:28.579 --> 00:11:29.949
I can demonstrate it."

00:11:29.949 --> 00:11:31.959
So after running a two hour workshop with
them,

00:11:31.959 --> 00:11:33.110
I gave them this challenge.

00:11:33.110 --> 00:11:35.259
And this is the design brief.

00:11:35.259 --> 00:11:38.200
Essentially it says: Your job is to create
as much value

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:39.630
possible.

00:11:39.630 --> 00:11:43.750
Value measured in any way you want, in two
hours,

00:11:43.750 --> 00:11:46.759
starting with the contents of one trashcan.

00:11:46.759 --> 00:11:48.769
You can pick whatever
trashcan you want.

00:11:48.769 --> 00:11:53.440
So basically we're taking something that doesn't
even have zero value, it has negative value.

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:56.920
Right, this is, basically
you pay people to take away the trash, so

00:11:56.920 --> 00:11:57.970
we're going to take this.

00:11:57.970 --> 00:12:00.680
Take something that people thinks has no value,
and create as much value

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:02.899
as possible in two hours.

00:12:02.899 --> 00:12:07.319
So to raise the stakes a little bit, I also
invited, um, my colleagues around the world

00:12:07.319 --> 00:12:11.230
and the U.S. and Asia, Europe,
Latin America, to participate with their students

00:12:11.230 --> 00:12:12.230
as well.

00:12:12.230 --> 00:12:14.660
So we now had thousands of students from around
the world

00:12:14.660 --> 00:12:16.880
who are participating at the same time.

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:19.400
Each one picking whatever
garbage can they wanted, and creating as much

00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:22.029
value as possible in two hours.

00:12:22.029 --> 00:12:25.660
They had, basically, some time to think about
it, but as soon as they opened up,

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:29.370
you know, spilled out the garbage can, they
had two hours.

00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:31.350
Interesting thing happened that was unexpected.

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:35.529
The students ended up spending
a bunch of time at the beginning, discussing,

00:12:35.529 --> 00:12:40.050
and thinking about and debating
what value meant to them.

00:12:40.050 --> 00:12:44.691
They thought about happiness and health,
about community and knowledge, and of course

00:12:44.691 --> 00:12:46.490
financial security.

00:12:46.490 --> 00:12:50.970
And that ended up helping them really frame
the way they looked at whatever garbage they

00:12:50.970 --> 00:12:51.970
had.

00:12:51.970 --> 00:12:54.699
So you wanna see what some of the students
did?

00:12:54.699 --> 00:12:55.699
Okay.

00:12:55.699 --> 00:12:56.699
So this is a team.

00:12:56.699 --> 00:12:57.699
The first one
is from Ecuador.

00:12:57.699 --> 00:13:00.670
And they picked a garbage can
I probably would not have picked.

00:13:00.670 --> 00:13:03.240
It's a garbage can filled with yard waste.

00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:06.709
All sorts of leaves,
Wow, what could you do with this?

00:13:06.709 --> 00:13:08.180
I mean this is, you know, this is compost.

00:13:08.180 --> 00:13:13.389
Well these students looked at it a different
way, and created a mural

00:13:13.389 --> 00:13:15.040
with all of this yard waste.

00:13:15.040 --> 00:13:16.130
Pretty cool?

00:13:16.130 --> 00:13:17.130
Beautiful.

00:13:17.130 --> 00:13:23.050
There was a girl in Ireland who found
a garbage can filled with old socks that her

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:25.910
mom
was throwing out from her brother's sock drawer.

00:13:25.910 --> 00:13:26.980
All these holey old socks.

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:30.350
Boy, I probably wouldn't have picked that
one either.

00:13:30.350 --> 00:13:32.990
She took them, cut them apart, sewed them
back together,

00:13:32.990 --> 00:13:35.380
and made a beautiful sweater.

00:13:35.380 --> 00:13:36.380
Pretty cool?

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:39.440
Wow, who thought of making a sweater out of
old socks?

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:41.079
Pretty interesting idea.

00:13:41.079 --> 00:13:46.290
And then there was a team in Japan,
and this team went to the local laundromat

00:13:46.290 --> 00:13:48.560
and they got the plastic bags and the hangers.

00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:52.550
And they realized there was a spot on the
campus

00:13:52.550 --> 00:13:53.790
that was called "the dead zone."

00:13:53.790 --> 00:13:57.980
It was part of a big grassy hill
that was all kind of damp because of the grass

00:13:57.980 --> 00:13:59.029
was always just a little bit wet.

00:13:59.029 --> 00:14:02.000
And people didn't want to sit there because
it was kind of uncomfortable.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.160
So they made these mats that you could sit
on,

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:06.250
and you could roll them up and keep them in
your backpack.

00:14:06.250 --> 00:14:08.380
And whenever you wanted, you'd roll them out.

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:11.250
But they didn't stop there,
they decided to start an entire community

00:14:11.250 --> 00:14:17.261
around this, and they painted games
like Twister, on these mats so that when you

00:14:17.261 --> 00:14:22.130
go there
and you rolled out your, your mat and sat

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:24.540
on it,
you could play a game with someone else there.

00:14:24.540 --> 00:14:28.379
In fact, what ended up happening was the local
vendors started coming by,

00:14:28.379 --> 00:14:31.870
and selling coffee and pastries and they ended
up creating an entire community

00:14:31.870 --> 00:14:34.839
around this area that had really been a dead
zone.

00:14:34.839 --> 00:14:39.730
So, we've talked about framing problems, connecting
and combining ideas,

00:14:39.730 --> 00:14:41.000
challenging assumptions.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.250
But the fact is, your imagination is NOT enough.

00:14:44.250 --> 00:14:47.180
These are great places to start.

00:14:47.180 --> 00:14:50.480
You need to start with a base of knowledge.

00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:54.589
And if you do not have a base of knowledge,
then you don't have any tools

00:14:54.589 --> 00:14:56.650
for your imagination.

00:14:56.650 --> 00:14:58.889
This is incredibly important.

00:14:58.889 --> 00:15:02.300
Your knowledge
is a tool box for your imagination.

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:05.019
The more you know, the more you have
to work with.

00:15:05.019 --> 00:15:08.339
Now the interesting thing is, it doesn't have
to be something that is even

00:15:08.339 --> 00:15:10.610
directly related to the problem you are trying
to solve.

00:15:10.610 --> 00:15:14.240
In fact, uh, at lunch
I had a very fascinating conversation with

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:16.709
some of the Googlers here,
about neurophysiology.

00:15:16.709 --> 00:15:20.500
And we ended up talking about really single
cell

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:23.889
neurophysiology and talking about all the
lessons you can learn

00:15:23.889 --> 00:15:28.020
about organizations and social networking,
based on looking

00:15:28.020 --> 00:15:29.620
at individual nerve cells.

00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:30.620
Pretty cool?

00:15:30.620 --> 00:15:35.279
And I could talk about this
and share these ideas because I am a neurophysiologist.

00:15:35.279 --> 00:15:38.970
And the fact is,
you can bring knowledge from any field, but

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:41.709
you NEED something to work with.

00:15:41.709 --> 00:15:42.709
So how do we get knowledge?

00:15:42.709 --> 00:15:46.029
We get knowledge, of course, by going to lectures,
and reading books,

00:15:46.029 --> 00:15:47.380
and by going to school.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:48.380
But you know what?

00:15:48.380 --> 00:15:52.069
You also gain knowledge
by paying attention to the world.

00:15:52.069 --> 00:15:55.839
By being more observant
than anyone else.

00:15:55.839 --> 00:15:59.879
Because when you're paying attention,
you see problems that need to get solved,

00:15:59.879 --> 00:16:02.410
and you
often seen solutions that are right in front

00:16:02.410 --> 00:16:03.410
of you.

00:16:03.410 --> 00:16:05.110
Now, most people don't do this.

00:16:05.110 --> 00:16:07.490
In fact, magicians know this.

00:16:07.490 --> 00:16:09.579
This is why magicians play with your attention.

00:16:09.579 --> 00:16:14.120
They know that
a single, a hand gesture, or a little joke,

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:17.839
or pointing to someone
in the audience can totally distract you and

00:16:17.839 --> 00:16:20.019
you don't see
what's going on over here.

00:16:20.019 --> 00:16:22.430
On the other side, are comedians.

00:16:22.430 --> 00:16:26.480
Like Jerry Seinfeld, okay, who draw your attention
to things.

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:29.370
And they basically focus on things you didn't
pay attention to,

00:16:29.370 --> 00:16:33.860
like "did you ever notice that, standing in
line, or buying shoes".

00:16:33.860 --> 00:16:38.240
They pick something mundane, and it becomes
very funny with that

00:16:38.240 --> 00:16:40.180
level of scrutiny.

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:43.579
One of my favorite stories on how to increase
this comes from Stanford.

00:16:43.579 --> 00:16:48.339
One of my colleagues, Bob Segal,
who teaches classes all over the world.

00:16:48.339 --> 00:16:52.490
He takes students to
Madagascar, and to the Galapagos, and to Papua

00:16:52.490 --> 00:16:55.630
New Guinea
and he takes them on these excursions where

00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:57.329
they are essentially naturalists.

00:16:57.329 --> 00:17:00.579
Well, he does a class called "The Stanford
Safari".

00:17:00.579 --> 00:17:04.800
In a two week immersion program, the students
act like naturalists

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:05.800
at Stanford.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:12.300
Now, not only do they walk away learning everything,
from the pest controller and the organist,

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:15.560
and the librarian,
and all the presidents, you know, they end

00:17:15.560 --> 00:17:18.220
up getting this deep dive
into the university.

00:17:18.220 --> 00:17:22.200
They also walk away with an incredible
appreciation for what can happen when you

00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:25.170
actually pay attention.

00:17:25.170 --> 00:17:28.480
So we have our imagination, we have our knowledge
base,

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:34.100
but you also need the attitude that a problem
can get solved.

00:17:34.100 --> 00:17:40.050
If you do not have the confidence, the motivation,
the drive, to push through

00:17:40.050 --> 00:17:43.400
when a problem seems daunting, you are not
going to gain the knowledge,

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:46.430
you are not going to [inaudible] engage your
imagination,

00:17:46.430 --> 00:17:49.670
and you're not going to come up with a solution.

00:17:49.670 --> 00:17:54.530
Most people in the world view themselves as
puzzle builders.

00:17:54.530 --> 00:17:57.140
That means they're going out and getting all
the pieces they need

00:17:57.140 --> 00:18:00.270
and putting them together, to solve their
problem.

00:18:00.270 --> 00:18:02.070
But what's the problem with that?

00:18:02.070 --> 00:18:06.280
The problem with that is, if you are missing
a piece what happens?

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:08.430
Oops, it can't be done.

00:18:08.430 --> 00:18:12.040
And another thing with a puzzle is, you're
basically solving a problem that's a known

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:13.040
problem, right?

00:18:13.040 --> 00:18:15.510
A known
problem with a known solution.

00:18:15.510 --> 00:18:18.350
But what if you're trying to solve problems
that don't have a known

00:18:18.350 --> 00:18:19.350
solution?

00:18:19.350 --> 00:18:22.320
And in fact, they're really challenging?

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:25.510
Instead you need to view yourself as a quilt
maker.

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:29.000
Quilt makers are
people who take the resources that they have

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.371
available to them,
and they bring them to bear on the problem

00:18:32.371 --> 00:18:34.070
that they are trying to solve.

00:18:34.070 --> 00:18:38.020
And by looking at this image of this quilt,
I hope you realize

00:18:38.020 --> 00:18:41.000
that the results are truly remarkable.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:45.140
Much more remarkable than putting together
a known puzzle.

00:18:45.140 --> 00:18:48.010
It's interesting though, because we grow up,
and we usually hear

00:18:48.010 --> 00:18:52.060
Murphy's law, which says: If anything can
go wrong, what?

00:18:52.060 --> 00:18:53.320
It will, right?

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:56.280
In fact, often people, I don't want to ask
how many of you have this,

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:57.970
a poster in your office.

00:18:57.970 --> 00:19:01.750
But the idea is that this was a common thing,
that people had this poster that says if anything

00:19:01.750 --> 00:19:03.630
can go wrong, it will.

00:19:03.630 --> 00:19:07.310
Well, there's a problem with that, if that's
what you believe, then you're

00:19:07.310 --> 00:19:09.800
going to basically stop every time there's
a problem.

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:14.130
Peter Diamandes, who runs Singularity University
and X PRIZE Foundation,

00:19:14.130 --> 00:19:18.390
walked into one of his colleagues' offices,
and they had this sign up of Murphy's Law.

00:19:18.390 --> 00:19:23.650
He got so angry, he picked up a marking pen,
he went up and crossed out "it will" and wrote

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:24.700
"fix it!"

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:29.200
[crowd laughs]
If anything can go wrong, fix it.

00:19:29.200 --> 00:19:34.190
That is the mindset of a true innovator
and an entrepreneur, is someone who when they

00:19:34.190 --> 00:19:38.390
see a daunting challenge says,
"I am going to do everything in my power to

00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:39.910
fix it."

00:19:39.910 --> 00:19:45.300
So, this is your internal combustion engine
for creativity:

00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:49.072
your knowledge, your imagination, and your
attitude.

00:19:49.072 --> 00:19:51.920
Your knowledge is the toolbox for your imagination.

00:19:51.920 --> 00:19:56.620
Your imagination catalyzes the transformation
of your knowledge into new ideas.

00:19:56.620 --> 00:20:00.520
Your attitude is the spark that sets this
in motion.

00:20:00.520 --> 00:20:05.060
But you know what, you can be as creative
as you want, if you are not

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:09.820
in an environment that stimulates this, then
basically, you're hosed.

00:20:09.820 --> 00:20:12.550
And this is a problem in a lot of places,
because you get

00:20:12.550 --> 00:20:16.290
really creative people who really want to
solve big problems,

00:20:16.290 --> 00:20:18.590
and they are in environments that don't foster
it.

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:21.710
So you have to look at other pieces of the
puzzle.

00:20:21.710 --> 00:20:24.130
The first thing you have to look at is the
habitat.

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:27.750
Now you are incredibly fortunate here at Google
to have

00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:29.200
this incredible habitat.

00:20:29.200 --> 00:20:32.491
You walk around, and I just want
to take pictures at every corner, because

00:20:32.491 --> 00:20:35.370
you walk into the,
into the whole facility of the Googleplex

00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:39.790
and you say this
is a place that is designed for me to be creative.

00:20:39.790 --> 00:20:41.800
And this builds on the fact that when we're
kids,

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:43.870
it looks more like kindergarten, right?

00:20:43.870 --> 00:20:48.300
In fact the color scheme
matches that in kindergarten: primary colors,

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:52.280
red, lots of,
lots of things that stimulate your imagination,

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:55.510
lots of manipulatives, the space is very flexible.

00:20:55.510 --> 00:20:56.510
Really cool.

00:20:56.510 --> 00:20:59.170
When you go into kindergarten,
do you think that's a place you could be creative?...

00:20:59.170 --> 00:21:00.170
...Absolutely!

00:21:00.170 --> 00:21:03.390
But unfortunately, what happens is most of
us

00:21:03.390 --> 00:21:05.940
graduate from kindergarten, and we end up
in classrooms

00:21:05.940 --> 00:21:08.050
that look like this....

00:21:08.050 --> 00:21:11.470
...Wow...this is really disappointing, and,
you know,

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:15.390
the rows of chairs are lined up in, in straight
lines.

00:21:15.390 --> 00:21:16.810
They're bolted to the floor.

00:21:16.810 --> 00:21:19.330
This is to make it easy
for the teacher.

00:21:19.330 --> 00:21:21.350
So that it, you know, things are easy to clean
up.

00:21:21.350 --> 00:21:25.140
Do you think it makes it appropriate for creativity?

00:21:25.140 --> 00:21:28.000
No, and then we say,
you know, these kids, they're just not so

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:29.430
creative anymore.

00:21:29.430 --> 00:21:33.050
And then they get out of this; they graduate
from high school and college

00:21:33.050 --> 00:21:35.780
and they go to work in environments like this.

00:21:35.780 --> 00:21:41.080
Wow...and then again people say
our people are not creative.

00:21:41.080 --> 00:21:42.530
Well, this is ridiculous.

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:45.840
As I said, we're all creative
and we're waiting for this to be unleashed.

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:46.840
I feel fortunate enough.

00:21:46.840 --> 00:21:50.790
to work at Stanford, and our spaces are very
conducive

00:21:50.790 --> 00:21:51.790
to creativity.

00:21:51.790 --> 00:21:56.200
This is a picture of the D school at Stanford,
where we have, un, our ubiquitous red couches,

00:21:56.200 --> 00:21:57.500
the furniture all moves.

00:21:57.500 --> 00:21:58.780
It's not expensive.

00:21:58.780 --> 00:22:02.430
We have most of the furniture is from IKEA,
you know, uh,

00:22:02.430 --> 00:22:04.770
foam cubes that can be moved around.

00:22:04.770 --> 00:22:05.870
Lots of whiteboards.

00:22:05.870 --> 00:22:08.100
You walk into the space,
and you say: WOW.

00:22:08.100 --> 00:22:10.430
This is a place where I could be creative.

00:22:10.430 --> 00:22:13.080
And you know, here are some pictures of my
class, it looks like a kindergarten,

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:16.640
the students are working, actually on a pretty
complicated problem here, but they've

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:20.970
got the sort of material here, you know, Play
Doh and markers, and construction paper,

00:22:20.970 --> 00:22:25.290
or they're working on the floor, working on
a simulation game, and you know,

00:22:25.290 --> 00:22:27.250
AGAIN, it looks more like a kindergarten.

00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:29.590
And as we know, innovative companies
do this well.

00:22:29.590 --> 00:22:33.130
This is at IDEO, where when somebody leaves
to go on vacation,

00:22:33.130 --> 00:22:36.140
it is very likely that when they come back,
their office has been transformed.

00:22:36.140 --> 00:22:39.840
You go on a road trip, and you come back and
your office is now in the back of a van.

00:22:39.840 --> 00:22:42.720
You go on your honeymoon in Paris, and you
come back and your office looks like the Eiffel

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:43.790
Tower.

00:22:43.790 --> 00:22:45.230
This is NOT frivolous.

00:22:45.230 --> 00:22:50.540
This is a messaging that every single thing
that you do is ripe for creativity.

00:22:50.540 --> 00:22:54.670
And here's a picture, right, this is Google
in Zurich.

00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:57.630
I don't know exactly what these
pods are for, but they're very, obviously,

00:22:57.630 --> 00:22:59.880
you walk in and it feels very playful.

00:22:59.880 --> 00:23:05.890
Or at Pixar, where there's a slide going through
the middle of the building.

00:23:05.890 --> 00:23:08.760
So having an environment, a physical environment
is important.

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:12.520
You also need to think about the rules, the
rewards, the constraints,

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:13.820
the incentives.

00:23:13.820 --> 00:23:16.960
All of those things come into play, and those
things all

00:23:16.960 --> 00:23:19.350
to contribute to the types of habitats we
live in.

00:23:19.350 --> 00:23:23.640
But in addition,
we are really sensitive to the types of resources

00:23:23.640 --> 00:23:25.200
we have available to us.

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:26.460
Now, what are resources?

00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:28.790
Interesting thing is, here we are in Silicon
Valley,

00:23:28.790 --> 00:23:32.900
we think of resources, wow, we certainly have
a lot of money around, a lot of

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:34.750
money we can spend on projects.

00:23:34.750 --> 00:23:38.200
But resources come in so many different flavors.

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:43.770
Think of natural resources, think of communities,
think of processes that we have in place.

00:23:43.770 --> 00:23:44.840
Each of these can be leveraged.

00:23:44.840 --> 00:23:49.540
And one of the problems is, people who don't
live here often think that they need to replicate

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:51.100
what we're
doing in Silicon Valley.

00:23:51.100 --> 00:23:55.050
They think that the only types of resources
that are valuable are the ones that are found

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:56.050
here.

00:23:56.050 --> 00:23:58.690
But other parts of the world have equally
valuable resources

00:23:58.690 --> 00:24:01.580
that they need to learn to leverage.

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:05.870
So besides the habitat and the resources,
it's incredibly important

00:24:05.870 --> 00:24:11.330
to think about the culture, because the culture
in any organization

00:24:11.330 --> 00:24:17.240
affects everything you do, you think, you
feel, you act, is affected

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:18.630
by the culture.

00:24:18.630 --> 00:24:20.930
Now one of the most important pieces of a
culture

00:24:20.930 --> 00:24:23.500
is a willingness to experiment.

00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:26.040
To try lots of things,
and keep what works.

00:24:26.040 --> 00:24:29.980
And one of the problems is, that people often,
especially as an organization gets bigger

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:33.690
and bigger,
get more afraid of failing, and also get more

00:24:33.690 --> 00:24:37.720
afraid of showing
things to something, someone who's more senior

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:39.740
until it's fully baked.

00:24:39.740 --> 00:24:43.730
So they spend a lot of time, a lot of money,
a lot of energy, a lot of resources

00:24:43.730 --> 00:24:48.050
right, especially if you've got resources,
on making a project look finished.

00:24:48.050 --> 00:24:50.060
Well, there's a huge problem with this.

00:24:50.060 --> 00:24:52.340
The problem is, you might have committed to
something

00:24:52.340 --> 00:24:55.210
that's a bad idea, and now, you've put bunch
of time,

00:24:55.210 --> 00:24:58.240
money and energy into this, and in fact, when
you show something

00:24:58.240 --> 00:25:02.090
to someone and it looks finished, they are
much less likely

